'The sea is ours': Bolivia, which is surrounded by land, hopes the court will reopen a path to the Pacific
The sailors stand guard of the naval headquarters armed with ropes and chains in La Paz.
A public building has a blue-coloured ocean flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are lined with the motto: "The sea is ours right.
"Recovering it is a duty."
Across Bolivia, which is surrounded by land, the memory of the coast lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict remains clear - just as the desire for Bolivians to be able to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
That hope is perhaps at its highest in decades, as Bolivia expects a ruling from the international court of justice on 1 October after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and obviously is awaiting the result with a positive outlook," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ICJ's decision on large screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will find, in favour of Bolivia's claim, that - after decades of irregular talks - Chile is obliged to negotiate and give Bolivia a sovereign outlet.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president - facing a controversial battle for his re-election next year - also has a lot to lose in Monday's decision.
"We are very close to having access to the Pacific Ocean again," he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in favour of Bolivia - and that it would change little if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to grant the territory of Chile, and has established that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
That the ICJ's ruling arrives only six months after the final arguments were heard, indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from fanning Bolivia's cause, the last four years may not have been helpful.
"The issue of access to the sea has been seized by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
Morales's hostile rhetoric weakened any Chilean residual goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile, at some point, will continue to talk, but it will be very difficult to hold discussions after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that court decision-making was unusually fast.
On Monday, Bolivia will have an "extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the "opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - still one of Latin America's most popular presidents - was using the maritime issue as a political aid.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The judgment is an opportunity to see that we need to overcome the past."
