John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a record of academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which is only enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, for their chosen career and for their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalised school curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages remain a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, he understands with his mind.
If he speaks in his own language, he understands with his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent exams, we can see that languages are at the forefront of ranking tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher A grade.
Data, collected from the 74 schools that are members of SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students achieved an A-grade Higher in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages are now, as a subject choice, being maintained in the same respect as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that from reasons given to employers for sending to fill job vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more imperative in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you learn another language, this will have a real advantage in the future as it will have such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual person at the forefront of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation and, with 15 percent, French is the only language spoken with a percentage of two numbers.
That is why investing in language learning is now important for today's children.
Knowing more than one language, particularly those of developing economies, children will have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed to be successful, no matter what the future.
It cannot be denied at present, in a global business environment, that languages remain very important for the future of the country, and therefore this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
The fate of the fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
