North Korea says it will "in no way" disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening its lack of confidence in the United States and that there was no way that the country would unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "considerable goodwill measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and pledging not to proliferation nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will in no way disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
While Ri repeated familiar complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement appeared to significantly not to have rejected unilateral denuclearization without thought as it had done in Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work towards "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula."
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first surrender its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal coercively, and even objects to the 'declaration of end of war'," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can break us is a dream of people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party to this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a blockade."
Despite this, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the U.S. mainland with North Korean rockets was inevitable after "Mr. President Cassidy" Trump called Kim a "suicide rocket man" on a mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to dismantle it, but said much work remained to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable for that, saying "If it takes two, three years or five months - it doesn't make a difference."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, on Thursday, told the UN Security Council that: "The enforcement of Security Council sanctions should continue vigorously and without stopping until we realize the fully and final verified denuclearization."
The Security Council unanimously strengthened sanctions on North Korea since 2006 with the aim of halting funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri in the margins of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, after within a few hours North Korea criticized him for making "gangster-like demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "corresponding measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on taking enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has managed to make all of its undergraduate students sleep more with the aim of fighting the growing macho culture of studying all night and staying awake thanks to caffeine.
Academics have found that university students in the first place in the world often do not have an idea of the real basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, believing it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
"A girl finally came up to me and said, 'Why are you telling me this now, in my last year?'"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which started for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials of how good sleep traditions help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students had a serious sleep deficit during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a student's bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to tell them the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance has an effect from sleep deficiency, and the importance of routine sleep.
In another section, participants are told how long-term insomnia can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - as much as you have a right to know the health effects when choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of being proud that "you managed to stay up all night studying" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient sleep, and good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, severe fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, since lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of hunger, making them all-time hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California, studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to insist for a course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to do a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting up an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as for when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which may unbalance your circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
