Red Tide Update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, overgrowth conditions of algae in isolated areas are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide which is an overgrowth of algae extends about 130 miles of coastline from the upper Pinellas to the lower Lee countries.
The isolated areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites related to last week.
Red Tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations near the coast or offshore of Pinellas County have been reported in the past week, low to high concentrations offshore of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations offshore of Charatee County, background to high concentrations offshore of Charate County, background to high concentrations offshore of Charate County, and background to high concentrations offshore of Chara County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
